        <h3 data-uuid="e4d1c120e93443ecba0f8e02977cd5eb">Federalism</h3>
        <p data-uuid="8d503cea07fa49abaa47290aa1d7f592">The framers of the Constitution wanted a stronger national government, but they also wanted the states to continue to have an important role. They created a system called federalism, which divides power between the national government and the states. </p>
        <p data-uuid="ca7d3344f5f64f068f5964a2060fa27b">The Constitution assigns certain powers to the national, or federal, government. These are called delegated powers. National powers are designed to promote the general welfare, or common good—the needs and interests of the people as a whole. For example, by regulating trade and developing a uniform monetary system, the government creates conditions that allow businesses throughout the nation to prosper.</p>
        <p data-uuid="7096c1f3a3054d0692efa8063550eac0"> Reserved powers are those kept by the states. For example, states are responsible for creating local governments and holding elections. Concurrent powers are those shared by the federal and state governments.</p>
