        <p data-uuid="fbe2e702c06146b3a35c401c3523c1e8">Sometimes, Congress has had to stretch its delegated powers to deal with new or unexpected issues. A clause in the Constitution states that Congress may “make all Laws which shall be necessary and proper” for carrying out its duties. This clause, called the elastic clause—because it can be stretched (like elastic)—provides flexibility for the government. The federal government has used this clause to provide public services such as funding for the arts and humanities.</p>
